performers for this evening.

05:22.689 --> 05:26.392
Ladies and gentlemen,
it's Caleb and Alyson!

05:26.426 --> 05:27.927
- Hey!

05:27.960 --> 05:31.331
[cheers and applause]

05:31.364 --> 05:34.233
Now, Alyson, that is
everything we need to play

05:34.267 --> 05:36.069
a game of "Fool Us."

05:36.102 --> 05:38.271
- Great!
- Now, Alyson, remember,

05:38.304 --> 05:42.942
the object of this game
is to find the King of spades,

05:42.975 --> 05:45.712
wherever it happens
to be in the deck.

05:45.745 --> 05:49.315
And we'll do this with a little
help from Penn and Teller.

05:50.083 --> 05:53.419
Alyson, would you lift off
about half of those cards.

05:55.521 --> 05:58.124
And I'll place Penn and Teller
in at that exact location.

05:58.157 --> 06:00.460
You can actually drop the whole
pile right back on top.

06:00.493 --> 06:01.661
- Oh.

06:01.694 --> 06:03.229
- We'll sort of bury them
in the middle

06:03.262 --> 06:05.231
and hold it face
down in your hands.

06:05.264 --> 06:06.899
- Easier said than done.

06:06.933 --> 06:08.601
- You're doing great.

06:08.634 --> 06:12.105
Now, earlier, we had the real
Penn and Teller work together

06:12.138 --> 06:13.840
to create a playing card.

06:13.873 --> 06:15.475
That's how they chose
their card,

06:15.508 --> 06:17.343
and in a moment,
miniature Penn and Teller

06:17.377 --> 06:19.078
are gonna do the same thing.

06:19.112 --> 06:21.914
All you have to do is give the
cards a little shake like this.

06:21.948 --> 06:23.549
Perfect, a professional.

06:23.583 --> 06:26.853
Now you can spread the cards
face down across the table.

06:26.886 --> 06:28.020
- Aw, man.

06:28.054 --> 06:29.422
- You're doing good.
You're doing good.

06:29.455 --> 06:31.891
- I should really practice
during the down season.

06:31.924 --> 06:33.559
- We are hunting for those
Penn and Teller cards,

06:33.593 --> 06:35.728
I think I see one of them
poking out here.

06:35.762 --> 06:36.996
- I do too.
- There's Teller.

06:37.029 --> 06:38.464
- I see Teller!
- Keep spreading,

06:38.498 --> 06:39.532
I think there's Penn.
- Hey!

06:39.565 --> 06:41.134
- Something has happened,
Alyson!

06:41.167 --> 06:45.104
There is now one card
face down in between.

06:45.138 --> 06:47.273
That's the card
that they picked.

06:47.306 --> 06:50.943
And wouldn't it be amazing
if they picked the same card

06:50.977 --> 06:53.746
as the real Penn and Teller.
- Yeah.

06:53.780 --> 06:55.181
- Do you remember
what we're looking for?

06:55.214 --> 06:58.117
- The king of spades.
- The king of spades.

06:58.151 --> 07:00.520
Go ahead and turn it
over yourself.

07:00.553 --> 07:02.755
- What?
- You did it!

07:02.789 --> 07:05.858
[cheers and applause]

07:05.892 --> 07:10.129
Now, you are right, Alyson,
you won the game,

07:10.163 --> 07:11.764
so you win the trophy.

07:11.798 --> 07:13.366
- Yay!
- And let's give it up

07:13.399 --> 07:15.535
for Alyson Hannigan!

07:15.568 --> 07:17.403
[cheers and applause]

07:17.437 --> 07:19.639
- Ah.

07:19.672 --> 07:22.708
- Now, Alyson, I'm very happy
you won the game.

07:22.742 --> 07:23.843
- Me too.

07:23.876 --> 07:25.745
- And I'm glad
you earned the trophy.

07:25.778 --> 07:29.916
But I have to admit, I'm hoping
that maybe I can go home

07:29.949 --> 07:31.517
with the trophy
tonight as well.

07:31.551 --> 07:34.053
That's why there's one
more phase to this game.

07:34.086 --> 07:36.255
You see, when I was designing
all of these components

07:36.289 --> 07:38.357
for the game,
I tried to simulate

07:38.391 --> 07:41.260
this "Fool Us" experience
as closely as possible.

07:41.294 --> 07:42.695
But I don't just mean
"Fool Us" in general,

07:42.728 --> 07:46.332
I mean this specific
"Fool Us" experience.

07:46.365 --> 07:49.335
You see, even though
Penn and Teller

07:49.368 --> 07:51.137
could have worked together

07:51.170 --> 07:54.974
to select any one of these
52 playing cards,

07:55.007 --> 07:59.212
I knew that Teller
would want to go for a king.

07:59.245 --> 08:01.614
And that Penn would want
to go for the spades.

08:01.647 --> 08:06.452
And that together, they would
create the king of spades.

08:06.486 --> 08:09.722
- Ahh.

08:09.755 --> 08:11.591
Yay.
- And that's how you play

08:11.624 --> 08:14.193
"Penn & Teller:
Fool Us, Home Edition."

08:14.227 --> 08:16.896
- Aww.

08:16.929 --> 08:19.031
Caleb Wiles!

08:19.065 --> 08:22.068
[cheers and applause]

08:24.003 --> 08:26.105
This is so creative.
- Yes.

08:26.138 --> 08:29.509
My two passions in life
are magic and board games,

08:29.542 --> 08:31.611
so I thought I had
to combine the two

08:31.644 --> 08:32.879
if I was gonna
come on "Fool Us."

08:32.912 --> 08:34.847
It was many weekends
up late at night.

08:34.881 --> 08:36.682
It was a lot of work,
but I wouldn't have been able

08:36.716 --> 08:38.751
to do it without all my family
and friends helping me out.

08:38.784 --> 08:41.087
- And is it designed
to always win?

08:41.120 --> 08:43.456
- Yes, it was rigged
in your favor, Alyson.

08:43.489 --> 08:45.825
- That's my favorite type
of magic trick.

08:45.858 --> 08:48.461
Hopefully it's rigged
in your favor too.

08:48.494 --> 08:49.929
- We'll see.

08:49.962 --> 08:52.665
- All right, it's time to put
Penn and Teller on the spot.

08:52.698 --> 08:54.033
Guys!

08:54.066 --> 08:56.435
- Oh, we're so flattered.
What a lot of work.

08:56.469 --> 08:57.637
- Yes.
- That's beautiful.

08:57.670 --> 08:59.205
We don't even wanna talk
about your trick.

08:59.238 --> 09:00.840
We just wanna talk
about the home game.

09:00.873 --> 09:02.141
- Yes.

09:02.174 --> 09:04.410
- The home game seems
like such a great idea.

09:04.443 --> 09:06.078
It wouldn't only be
this trick, right?

09:06.112 --> 09:07.480
There would be other tricks.
- Sure, yeah.

09:07.513 --> 09:08.981
- So there would be
a whole index in there

09:09.015 --> 09:10.449
of how you pick which trick

09:10.483 --> 09:12.051
you're gonna do
and all of that,

09:12.084 --> 09:14.186
and is this
a durable home game?

09:14.220 --> 09:16.188
I mean, once you've played
with the deck for a while,

09:16.222 --> 09:18.925
would you have another deck
you could bring in after that,

09:18.958 --> 09:20.326
so it would never wear out?

09:20.359 --> 09:22.395
Just keep going,
playing the home game forever?

09:22.428 --> 09:24.096
- Yeah, yeah.
- Now, you'd been working

09:24.130 --> 09:25.831
on this for a while, right?
- Yeah.

09:25.865 --> 09:27.466
- So all the directions
that are in there,

09:27.500 --> 09:28.868
you have them memorized,
I'm sure.

09:28.901 --> 09:30.403
- I do.
- This is a great,

09:30.436 --> 09:31.771
great idea for "Fool Us."

09:31.804 --> 09:33.172
We'd be playing at home.

09:33.205 --> 09:36.208
I think you've worked out
absolutely all the problems,

09:36.242 --> 09:40.580
and as far as the trick,
we had a couple ideas in there.

09:40.613 --> 09:42.248
- Okay.
- About how you did it.

09:42.281 --> 09:45.851
- So based on those clues,
did they figure out your trick?

09:45.885 --> 09:49.221
- I have to say,
I was really hoping

09:49.255 --> 09:52.658
to go home
with a trophy tonight,

09:52.692 --> 09:54.927
so it's a good thing
I printed extras.

09:54.961 --> 09:57.797
- Done.
- Yay.

09:57.830 --> 09:59.131
Cheers.
- Yes.

09:59.165 --> 10:00.666
Aw, Caleb Wiles.

10:00.700 --> 10:02.001
- Thank you so much!

10:02.034 --> 10:04.070
Thank you!

10:04.103 --> 10:07.039
[cheers and applause]

10:07.073 --> 10:10.176
- More magicians take the stage
when we come back.

10:10.209 --> 10:12.578
And later on, Penn and Teller
perform too.

10:12.612 --> 10:13.913
Stick around.

